    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1933-10-19T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1933-10-19T00:00:00-05:00" n="398"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d398">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.512 Boats/50</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">German Embassy</gloss> to the <gloss
                            type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Translation]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p rend="flushleft">St. 1b</p>
                <p>With reference to the communication of August 1 of this year (811.512 Boats/45)
                    from the Acting Secretary of State,<note n="19" xml:id="d398fn19">Not
                        printed.</note> the German Embassy has the honor to request the Department
                    of State again for a decision with regard to the tax on vessels built abroad,
                    provided in the Revenue Act of 1932 (Section 761 (<hi rend="italic"
                        >b</hi>)).<note n="20" xml:id="d398fn20">47 Stat. 277.</note>
                </p>
                <p>The matter has been pending for more than a year without such a decision having
                    been secured so far, although the Department of State on its part had made “a
                    request” of the competent officials “for an early expression of their views”,
                    according to the communication of April 4th of this year.<note n="19"
                        xml:id="d398fn22">Not printed.</note>
                </p>
                <pb facs="0603" n="503" xml:id="pg_503"/>
                <p>The Embassy would be so much the more grateful for information, as a violation of
                    a provision of the German-American Commercial Treaty is involved,<note n="21"
                        xml:id="d398fn21">Treaty signed at Washington, December 8, 1923, <ref
                            target="frus1923v02#pg_29">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1923, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">ii</hi>, p. 29</ref>.</note> which is, in the
                    opinion of the Government, perfectly unambiguous.</p>
                <closer>
                    <dateline rendition="#left">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-10-19">October 19,
                            1933</date>.</dateline>
                </closer>
            </div>
